Introduction

In this assignment, I analyze how the three authors use suspense in their works to create horror. Suspense arouses excited expectation or uncertainty about what may happenâ€“a horrific event is certainly bad, but having to wait for the horrific event to happen is even worse because of the additional torment during the process of waiting. Therefore, it would be interesting to see how EAP, MWS, and HPL take advanage of suspense in their worksâ€“specifically, what are the similarities and differences among the authors in terms of the frequency that and literary devices with which they create suspense?

Data Cleaning

We first use the unnest_tokens() function to drop all punctuation and transform all words into lower case. At least for now, the punctuation isnâ€™t really important to our analysis â€“ we want to study the words. In addition, tidytext contains a dictionary of stop words, like â€œandâ€ or â€œnextâ€, that we will get rid of for our analysis, the idea being that the non-common words (â€¦maybe the SPOOKY words) that the authors use will be more interesting.

spooky_wrd <- unnest_tokens(spooky, word, text)%>%
              anti_join(stop_words, by = "word")

1. Suspenseful Words

First, letâ€™s look at how the authors use words to create suspense. To do this, we apply sentiment analysis using NRC sentiment lexion. â€œThe NRC Emotion Lexicon is a list of English words and their associations with eight basic emotions (anger, fear, anticipation, trust, surprise, sadness, joy, and disgust) and two sentiments (negative and positive). The annotations were manually done by crowdsourcing.â€ Since weâ€™re interested only in suspenseful words, we include in our analysis only words that fall into these categories of the NRC emtion lexicon: â€œfearâ€, â€œanticipationâ€, and â€œsurpriseâ€.

#filter out suspenseful words from the NRC emotion lexicon
nrc_suspense <- filter(get_sentiments('nrc'), sentiment == "fear"|sentiment =="anticipation"|sentiment =="surprise")
#now the spooky_word data frame contains only suspenseful words
suspense <- inner_join(spooky_wrd, nrc_suspense, by = "word")

1.3 idiosyncrasies are the best

What words does each author uniquely use?

In 1.1, we looked at how each author individually uses suspenseful words. In 1.2, we tried to add in a bit more comparison between the authors by looking at how the most frequently used suspenseful words are split between the authors. Now, we try to add in even more comparison between the authors, by uncovering the words that each author uniquely uses in comparison to other authors. Here, we use an TF-IDF(term frequency-inverse document frequency) approach to give more emphasis to words that are rare within the context of the entire dataset, in the hope that weâ€™ll discover words that are characteristic for a specific author.

frequency <-suspense %>%
  count(author, word)
tf_idf <- frequency %>%
  bind_tf_idf(word, author, n)
tf_idf %>%
  arrange(desc(tf_idf)) %>%
  mutate(word = factor(word, levels = rev(unique(word)))) %>%
  group_by(author) %>%
  top_n(20, tf_idf) %>%
  ungroup() %>%  
  ggplot(aes(word, tf_idf, fill = author)) +
  geom_col() +
  labs(x = NULL, y = "tf-idf") +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  facet_wrap(~ author, ncol = 3, scales = "free") +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(y = "TF-IDF values")
ggsave("unique words by author.png",plot =last_plot(),path = '../figs/',width = 20, height = 20, units = "cm")

Each authorâ€™s unique words again confirm their respective literary themes, which I have discussed above. -MWS has many words related to Romantic ideas such as passion and familyâ€“â€œpassionâ€(or â€œpassionateâ€),â€œangelâ€,â€œfestivalâ€,â€œorphanâ€,â€œloverâ€,â€œmaternalâ€,â€œmarryâ€. -one of HPLâ€™s central themes involves religion and superstition, therefore the â€œcultâ€,â€œhellishâ€, and â€œdeamonâ€. -EAP is generally considered the inventor of the detective fiction genre. 2.3 semicolons to the rescue

Besides commas, semicolons are also often used to insert breaks into a sentence.Previously, we discovered that EAP loves commas while HPL seems to avoid them. Does the same pattern re-establish itself when it comes to semicolons?

When it comes to semicolons, HPL again has more sentences with no or one semicolon than the other two authors, and he has fewer sentences with many semicolons.

HPLâ€™s distribution is narrower and peaks towards larger num_char_per_semicolon values, meaning that most of his sentences tend NOT to have frequent semicolons.

So whatâ€™s the story behind using commas VS semicolons? It seems that HPL simply does not like any breaks in his sentences, regardless of whether the break comes with a comma or a semicolon. However, EAP seeems to have a special preference for the kind of breaks(or the staccato effects) created by commas, as he is no longer the top user when it comes to semicolons. MWS now becomes the champion of semicolons.

In the analysis of commas, I have already compared EAPâ€™s and HPLâ€™s typical sentence structures. Now, based on the analysis of semicolons, I make a hypothesis about MWSâ€™s typical sentence structure by comparing it to EAPâ€™s and HPLâ€™s.

To understand the stylistic differences between the authors, it is important to first understand the difference in effects that a comma and a semicolon create. A comma creates more suspense than a semicolon, because it tells the reader that the sentence is far from ending. A semicolon, on the other hand, indicates a small logical ending in itself, even though the larger sentence has not ended. If a period indicates â€œfull stopâ€, a semicolon is like a â€œhalf stopâ€.

Armored with the above knowledge, letâ€™s continue to make some bold hypotheses.

While MWS and EAP both insert breaks into their sentences, EAP takes a particular liking to the staccato style, where his sentences resemble a series of short, detached musical notes, almost to the extent of being choppy. His sentences seem to be spoken by someone who, just, climbed, ten, flights, of, stairs, and, canâ€™t, catch, their, breath. An example:

Her sentences resemble normal human speech; the person speaks and pauses at places where or intervals when he thinks he has reached a logical semi-conclusion, or when he needs to catch his breath.
